ConfigMaps wrap those JSON files for Kubernetes. You have two options:

Option A – manually paste JSON (simpler, more manual)
Example: infra/k8s/monitoring/grafana/configmaps/grafana-dashboards-infra-prod.yaml:

text
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: grafana-dashboards-infra
  namespace: monitoring
  labels:
    grafana_dashboard: "1"
data:
  home.json: |
    { ... prod/infra/home.json content ... }
  k8s-overview.json: |
    { ... prod/infra/k8s-overview.json content ... }
Similarly, grafana-dashboards-myapp-prod.yaml for prod/myapp/*.json, and equivalents for dev/staging. kube‑prometheus‑stack will mount each ConfigMap into /var/lib/grafana/dashboards/{infra,myapp} based on your dashboardsConfigMaps values.

Pros: trivial to implement.
Cons: diff is a bit noisy (embedded JSON).

Option B – generate ConfigMaps from files (better for scaling)
You keep JSON as files, and use a generator (kustomize configMapGenerator, small script, or Helm) to build ConfigMaps from those files. Example with kustomize approach is commonly used in GitOps